          <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" vspace="0" hspace="0">
  <tr><td width="2" height="15"><img src="/lotr/gfx/center_column/1.gif" width="2" height="25"></td>
    <td width="700" background="/lotr/gfx/cloud/redcc.gif" height="15" valign="bottom"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr><td><font face="Tolk, Times, serif" class="h1font"><font color="#C46161">Articles</font></B></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td width="2"></td><td valign="top"> 
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5"><tr><td><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont">
 <font face="Tolk, Times, serif" class="h1font"> The Ruling Ring vs. Isildurs Bane<br></font><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8614'>marc "ShotguNazgul" LALAGUE</A></font><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 29, 2001</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"> DO NOT RATE UNLESS YOU HAVE READ THIS WHOLE ARTICLE<br>
<br>
I have been playing LOTR for quite some time now. I bought a bunch of cards and i have a few pretty good decks. I understand the rules and i have much experience with other card games. However, when I got an Isildur&#39;s Bane in a pack I was baffled. It is much different than the common one, and i tried to see how it fit. I know it combos well with sting, but it also doesnt. i like sting because you can look at their hand, and Isidur&#39;s Bane lets you do that an extra time. It is also good against archery because he can suck it up more effectively. But the extra burden really makes it kinda shakey. If you look at their hand with sting, then you can plan everyting out perfectly because you know what +STR events they have in their hand. If looking at their hand i know that frodo can survive a fight 100%, usually i step up with frodo and just add a burden, which is fine. With Isildur&#39;s, however, you take 2 burdens, which is much much worse. <br>
<br>
Vs. The Uruk-Hai:<br>
  Uruk-Hai are very popular in my area, so Isildur&#39;s would add 4 burdens if i step up with frodo. Usually against Uruk-Hai,Frodo taking 2 burdens (using the common ring) can prevent the death of a key character. However, The 4 burdens usually means that frodo can never fight again, and if he does, he will be corrupted. This is why the common ring is better against the Uruk-Hai in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Vs. The Nazgul:<br>
  Isildur&#39;s Bane is also worse against the Nazgul. if your Frodo Takes 4 wounds, then you have to be wearing the ring at all times. There are tons of cards that gain advantage if the ring-bearer wears the one ring, Return To Its Master being an automatic loss.<br>
<br>
Vs. The Moria Orcs:<br>
  Since Sting removes Twilight against Moria Orcs, Isildur&#39;s Bane becomes slightly better than the common one. However, the Moria Player will often try to swarm you, and altough Sting prevents you from being overwhelmed, you take double the burdens. It will not be difficult for them to be constantly adding burdens and eventually cause you to lose the game.<br>
<br>
Vs. The Sauron Orcs:<br>
  Against The Sauron Orcs, Isildur&#39;s Bane still doesn&#39;t help very much. Sauron Orcs will undoubtedly be killing off your fellowship as you move along the adventure path, so frodo will be fighting more often as the game goes on. The extra Burdens can really make the difference against sauron orcs, and since Sauron Orcs have their nasty Burden-adding conditions Isildur&#39;s Bane makes it too easy to be corrupted.<br>
<br>
The Verdict:<br>
  Well, you&#39;ve seen why i do not like Isildur&#39;s Bane, but i still have not taken sides on this matter. My playing style is the reason that i currently like the Ruling Ring more than Isildur&#39;s Bane. I use 2-3 Sting in every deck I play, and I usually use it to look at their hand during each of my fellowship phases. Whether or not i remove twilight with it, I make sure they don&#39;t have enough + STR pumpers to overwhelm Frodo. If they do, I sit back with Frodo, and if they do not, then I have the option of using Frodo as a fighter. There have been many times where fighting with frodo has prevented the death of one member of my fellowship, and is a very good deal at the price of one burden. As you can probably tell, taking two burdens is just not worth it for me. And using Sting 1 extra time just isn&#39;t amazing enough for me to like Isildur&#39;s Bane.<br>
<br>
Response:<br>
  If you do not agree with what I have said, please tell me why! The reason i posted this article was to show my view and see if someone can make me realize sometihg about the Rare ring i Did not see a first. Your Input would be greatly appreciated. Thank you for Reading my first Article for this site, I hope you found it useful!<br>
<br>
Marc &quot;ShotguNazgul&quot; Lalague<br>
